# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: broadcast-channel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] The **Broadcast Channel API** allows basic communication between browsing contexts (that is, *windows*, *tabs*, *frames*, or *iframes*) and workers on the same origin.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] By creating a `BroadcastChannel` object, you can receive any messages that are posted to it.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] You don't have to maintain a reference to the frames or workers you wish to communicate with: they can "subscribe" to a particular channel by constructing their own `BroadcastChannel` with the same name, and have bi-directional communication between all of them.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] A client joins a broadcast channel by creating a `BroadcastChannel` object.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] Its constructor takes one single parameter: the *name* of the channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] If it is the first to connect to that broadcast channel name, the underlying channel is created.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] It is enough to call the `postMessage()` method on the created `BroadcastChannel` object, which takes any object as an argument.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] Data sent to the channel is serialized using the structured clone algorithm.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] That means you can send a broad variety of data objects safely without having to serialize them yourself.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] The API doesn't associate any semantics to messages, so it is up to the code to know what kind of messages to expect and what to do with them.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] When a message is posted, a `message` event is dispatched to each `BroadcastChannel` object connected to this channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] To leave a channel, call the `close()` method on the object.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] This disconnects the object from the underlying channel, allowing garbage collection.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] The Broadcast Channel API's self-contained interface allows cross-context communication.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] It can be used to detect user actions in other tabs within a same origin, like when the user logs in or out.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] The messaging protocol is not defined and the different browsing contexts need to implement it themselves; there is no negotiation nor requirement from the specification.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcast-channel-api] Represents a named channel that any browsing context of a given origin can subscribe to.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] The **`postMessage()`** method of the `BroadcastChannel` interface sends a message, which can be of any kind of `Object`, to each listener in any browsing context with the same origin.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] The message is transmitted as a `message` event targeted at each `BroadcastChannel` bound to the channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] The data is serialized using the structured clone algorithm.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] This means you can pass a broad variety of data objects safely to the destination window without having to serialize them yourself.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] Thrown if the `BroadcastChannel` has already been closed.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel-postmessage] Thrown if any part of the input data is not serializable.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] The **`BroadcastChannel`** interface represents a named channel that any browsing context of a given origin can subscribe to.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] It allows communication between different documents (in different windows, tabs, frames or iframes) of the same origin.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Messages are broadcasted via a `message` event fired at all `BroadcastChannel` objects listening to the channel, except the object that sent the message.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Creates an object linking to the named channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Returns a string, the name of the channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Sends the message, of any type of object, to each `BroadcastChannel` object listening to the same channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Closes the channel object, indicating it won't get any new messages, and allowing it to be, eventually, garbage collected.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Fired when a message arrives on the channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Also available via the `onmessage` property.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Fired when a message arrives that can't be deserialized.
[src:broadcast-channel/broadcastchannel] Also available via the `onmessageerror` property.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:broadcast-channel/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] The **`message`** event of the `BroadcastChannel` interface fires when a message arrives on that channel.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] A string representing the origin of the message emitter.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] A string representing a unique ID for the event.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] A *message event source*, which is either a WindowProxy, a `MessagePort`, or a `ServiceWorker` object representing the message emitter.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] An array of `MessagePort` objects representing the ports associated with the channel the message is being sent through (where appropriate, e.g., in channel messaging or when sending a message to a shared worker).
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] In this example there's a "sender" `<iframe>` that broadcasts the contents of a `<textarea>` when the user clicks a button.
[src:broadcast-channel/message-event] There are two "receiver" iframes that listen to the broadcast message and write the result into a `<div>` element.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:broadcast-channel/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
